posts.text:
﻿
크라운( Crown ) • 치관부(치아머리)의 모든 치면을 감싸는 형태의 수복물을 말합니다.
• 근관치료한 치아나 금이 간 치아를 씌워 보호해주는 경우나 크게 파절되거나 우식이 큰 치아를 수복하는 경우에 크라운 치료를 하게 됩니다.
브릿지( Bridge ) • 남아있는 치아를 이용해 상실된 치아를 수복하는 인공적 대체물입니다.
• 흔히 걸어 넣는다고 표현합니다.
• 상실된 치아 앞뒤의 치아를 깎아서 씌우면서 상실된 치아를 대체하는 보철물을 장착합니다. ​
​
​Dental crowns are fixed to the outer surface of the tooth to restore shape, strength, function and appearance. They encase a tooth that has been badly damaged or decayed and are cemented on to the surface of the teeth. Since dental crowns cover the entire visible aspect of a tooth, a dental crown in effect becomes the tooth’s new outer surface. Crowns can be made out of porcelain, zirconia (a very hard ceramic), metal (a gold or other metal alloy), or a combination of both.
​
Your dentist may prescribe a crown to you to: Replace a large filling when there isn’t enough tooth remaining
Protect a weak tooth from fracturing
Restore a fractured tooth
Attach a bridge
Cover a dental implant
Cover a discoloured or poorly shaped tooth
Cover a tooth that has had root canal treatment
How does the treatment work? Your dentist will numb the area surrounding the tooth with a local anaesthetic. The tooth will be filed down, and an impression of it taken, to construct your crown to exact specifications. The crown is then cemented into place. There is little discomfort associated with getting a crown.
Crowns are made of extremely durable materials, yet are still subject to decay and daily wear and tear. Maintaining a good oral health routine will keep your crown healthy for as long as possible.

posts.text:
"Entering and exiting" is based on dualism.
On one hand, you are trying to fill your molecular body
in a molecular world with the energy of the universe and emit that energy.
On the other hand, you are one with the Universe
taking its energy as your own and emitting that.
Which energy is powerful between the two?
You'd emit more powerful energy
when you are one with the universe, right?
When you fill yourself with the energy of the universe,
you'll only be using your own power,
while the power of the universe lies outside of you.
In this case, you are blocking yourself from the universe, creating a wall in between.
Qigong practitioners do not heal others because treating others makes them lose their own qi.
Let's say that you trained and filled yourself with this much qi.
If you use that qi to help someone else heal, then you are losing that much qi from yourself.
That means you have to train even more to refill the lost qi.
Water flows from higher ground to a lower ground.
The same is true for qi. You must lose qi in order to heal others.

posts.title: Park Geun-hye Spending the Chuseok Holiday Alone in Prison
posts.text:
It looks like former President Park Geun-hye (65) will be spending the first holiday in the detention center alone.
According to the Korea Correctional Services under the Ministry of Justice on October 1, the prisoners in 52 correctional facilities nationwide will be allowed to see their families for two days-October 2 and 7-during this year's Chuseok holidays, which last from October 2 to 8.
Former President Park, who has been detained at Seoul Detention Center from March, will be among these prisoners, but the former president has added her younger sister, Park Geun-ryeong and younger brother, Park Ji-man on the list of people she refuses to see.
It is also unlikely for the former president to spend the holidays with other inmates. On the morning of October 4, Chuseok, the prisoners will jointly take part in a traditional ritual remembering their ancestors, at Seoul Detention Center. But former President Park, who has yet to be convicted, cannot attend.
The correctional service does not allow a prisoner on trial to take part in the joint ritual, due to concerns of coming into contact with an accomplice. In addition, members of the legal circle believe that the former president would not want such engagements, anyways.
Park can watch a special movie, which the prison's internal broadcasting channel, Boramae Broadcasting, will air, a different film every day during the Chuseok holidays. From October 2 to 8, they will air Iron Man 2, Iron Man 3, Ode to My Father, Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them, Roaring Currents, Criminal Designer, and Train to Busan respectively in this order. Ode to My Father, scheduled to be aired on October 4, is a film that the former president had praised putting the stress on patriotism, when she publicly viewed the film.
On the morning of Chuseok, she will have a breakfast of bread, soup, salad, and milk according to her prescribed diet. On this day, she will be served songpyeon�rice cakes steamed over pine leaves, a traditional Korean dish enjoyed on Chuseok-as a special treat.

posts.title: baseball-retiring player
posts.text:
Retiring baseball legend rues 'heart being ripped out' over end of career
DAEGU, Oct. 3 (Yonhap) -- About to call it quits after a record-breaking career in South Korean baseball on Tuesday, Samsung Lions slugger Lee Seung-yuop said he felt like his "heart was getting ripped out."
Lee was scheduled to play his final Korea Baseball Organization (KBO) game later in the day against the Nexen Heroes at Daegu Samsung Lions Park in Daegu, 300 kilometers southeast of Seoul. Daegu is also Lee's hometown and he's spent his entire 15-year KBO career with the Lions, with an eight-season stint in Japan's Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB) from 2004 to 2011.
At a press conference before the first pitch, Lee said baseball has been "everything" to him and he hated the feeling he had Tuesday morning.
Samsung Lions' slugger Lee Seung-yuop speaks at a press conference before his final Korea Baseball Organization game at Daegu Samsung Lions Park in Daegu on Oct. 3, 2017. (Yonhap)
"I feel like my heart is getting ripped out," Lee said. "I was able to maintain my composure until yesterday, but this morning, I felt strange. I've gained so much from baseball, and I've tried my absolute best to become the best player I could be. I wouldn't be here without the game of baseball."
Lee, 41, retiring as the KBO's all-time leader in home runs with 465 before Tuesday's game. He's also top in runs scored, RBIs, doubles and total bases.
He still holds the single-season record for home runs with 56, set in 2003.
Lee said he'd been hoping to add to his gaudy offensive numbers in his final game, but once the last day arrived, he just wanted to give his best effort and see what happened.
"Since this wraps up my 23-year professional career, I'd like to play the best I can before the fans," Lee said.
Lee thanked his parents for taking care of his mind and body, and a slew of coaches and managers he's had over his illustrious career. Lee also had fans come from Japan to watch his final game, and thanked them for their support throughout his up-and-down NPB career.
Lee remained a productive designated hitter in his final season. He entered Tuesday's game batting .278 with 22 home runs and 84 RBIs. And last year, he had 27 homers and 118 RBIs -- his most since 144 in 2003 -- while batting .303.
Asked if he was leaving the game prematurely, Lee said he wanted to give the Lions a chance to rebuild, noting that the team has finished ninth among 10 teams in each of the past two seasons.
Samsung Lions' slugger Lee Seung-yuop takes a bow at the start of a press conference before his final Korea Baseball Organization game at Daegu Samsung Lions Park in Daegu on Oct. 3, 2017. (Yonhap)
"It was time for me to leave, and if I hadn't decided to retire on my own terms, I think it would have been hard for the club to bring it up first," Lee said. "Though we won the championship my first year back from Japan in 2012, we were ninth the last two years. I feel responsible as one of the veterans, and the team needs a change. And it can only happen if I retire now."
Lee also said he hoped the Lions' minor leaguers would develop fast and fill his void, adding, "I am hoping they will be able to turn the fortunes around for the Lions."
Lee kept mum on his post-retirement plans, though he did say he'll never leave baseball.
"I've been talking to many different people; I could go study the game at some place, or I could become a television analyst," Lee said. "One thing is for sure -- I'll spend the rest of my life as a baseball man. I'll find a way to make the Lions and Korean baseball better. Baseball is my life."

posts.author: 경향신문 | 네이버 뉴스
posts.title: MB’s Cheong Wa Dae Also Behind Defense Security Command's Online Operations
posts.text:
The military's Defense Security Command (DSC) had organized a unit to post online comments and conducted operations to manipulate public opinion upon orders from Cheong Wa Dae in the Lee Myung-bak government. An internal investigation by the Defense Security Command officially confirmed such facts for the first. Under the Lee Myung-bak government, state agencies-from Cheong Wa Dae to the National Intelligence Service (NIS), the military's Cyber Command, and the Defense Security Command-were mobilized in an illegal attempt to manipulate online public opinion. A prosecutors' investigation of relevant officials in Cheong Wa Dae and the defense command at the time is now inevitable.
According to the facts that the Kyunghyang Shinmun confirmed through the Minjoo Party of Korea lawmaker Rhee Cheol-hee, a member of the parliamentary National Defense Committee, on September 29, a recent internal investigation by the Defense Security Command confirmed that an overseas public relations team, which was in operation from 2010 to 2012, carried out online operations and posted online comments. The Cheong Wa Dae Office of the Secretary for New Media Promotion drew up "Plans to Utilize Military Resources Skilled in Languages for Overseas Promotion in G20 Countries" in September 2009, and according to the plans, the defense command created an overseas PR team with 24 military personnel proficient in a foreign language and 14 of the command's own personnel the following January.
The official task of the overseas PR team was to obtain promotional information for the G20 Summit (Nov. 2010) and the Nuclear Security Summit (Mar. 2012) scheduled to be held in South Korea from Cheong Wa Dae and the Korean Culture and Information Services and translate and post them on overseas websites. However, the defense command investigation team revealed that the overseas PR team not only worked to promote state administration, but also engaged in all sorts of online operations including, online comments on entertainers and politicians included on a blacklist managed by the intelligence service.
According to the transcripts of a conversation between Lee Tae-ha, former head of psychological warfare in the military's Cyber Command and Ok Do-gyeong, a former commander (The conversation is presumed to have taken place in July 2014.), obtained from lawmaker Rhee, Lee Tae-ha said, "The Defense Security Command created an illegal psychological warfare unit and they attended and talked at an MB (former President Lee Myung-bak) Cheong Wa Dae meeting." He went on to say, "If I release this, you (Defense Security Command) are dead. The entire organization will have to go." His words claim that creating a unit in charge of online comments within the defense command was illegal, and the military's internal investigation officially confirmed that such irregularities actually took place.
Apart from the overseas PR team, the defense command created a unit for online comments with a total of 250 people, 4-5 people per unit in 2009, the early days of the Lee Myung-bak government. The command ran this organization until November 2010, and they responded to the Yongsan disaster, North Korean nuclear and missile issues, and the sinking of ROKS Cheonan. Those in this unit used other people's IDs, such as their relatives and friends, to post the online comments.
Lawmaker Rhee said, "What is important is what the Defense Security Command did while communicating with Cheong Wa Dae and using overseas promotion as an excuse. The prosecutors need to thoroughly identify the truth."

﻿ Press Release: The Nobel Prize in Physics 2017 3 October 2017
The Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences has decided to award the Nobel Prize in Physics 2017 with one half to
Rainer Weiss LIGO/VIRGO Collaboration
and the other half jointly to
Barry C. Barish LIGO/VIRGO Collaboration
and
Kip S. Thorne LIGO/VIRGO Collaboration
"for decisive contributions to the LIGO detector and the observation of gravitational waves"
Gravitational waves finally captured On 14 September 2015, the universe’s gravitational waves were observed for the very first time. The waves, which were predicted by Albert Einstein a hundred years ago, came from a collision between two black holes. It took 1.3 billion years for the waves to arrive at the LIGO detector in the USA.
The signal was extremely weak when it reached Earth, but is already promising a revolution in astrophysics. Gravitational waves are an entirely new way of observing the most violent events in space and testing the limits of our knowledge.
LIGO, the Laser Interferometer Gravitational-Wave Observatory , is a collaborative project with over one thousand researchers from more than twenty countries. Together, they have realised a vision that is almost fifty years old. The 2017 Nobel Laureates have, with their enthusiasm and determination, each been invaluable to the success of LIGO. Pioneers Rainer Weiss and Kip S. Thorne , together with Barry C. Barish , the scientist and leader who brought the project to completion, ensured that four decades of effort led to gravitational waves finally being observed.
In the mid-1970s, Rainer Weiss had already analysed possible sources of background noise that would disturb measurements, and had also designed a detector, a laser-based interferometer, which would overcome this noise. Early on, both Kip Thorne and Rainer Weiss were firmly convinced that gravitational waves could be detected and bring about a revolution in our knowledge of the universe.
Gravitational waves spread at the speed of light, filling the universe, as Albert Einstein described in his general theory of relativity. They are always created when a mass accelerates, like when an ice-skater pirouettes or a pair of black holes rotate around each other. Einstein was convinced it would never be possible to measure them. The LIGO project’s achievement was using a pair of gigantic laser interferometers to measure a change thousands of times smaller than an atomic nucleus, as the gravitational wave passed the Earth.
So far all sorts of electromagnetic radiation and particles, such as cosmic rays or neutrinos, have been used to explore the universe. However, gravitational waves are direct testimony to disruptions in spacetime itself. This is something completely new and different, opening up unseen worlds. A wealth of discoveries awaits those who succeed in capturing the waves and interpreting their message.
